        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested RMS is the RMS achieved by using the minimum allowed polarization track (3 hours).

The RMS of 38 uJy/bm will allow robust detections of polarization down to the 1% level in all three sources, both at 0.36" resolution as well as at 0.08" resolution (see Table 1 for the polarization SNR values for each source at each resolution).  1% is a very conservative estimate; we expect the polarization to be significantly higher, based on previous CARMA observations.  The Stokes I flux predictions at 0.08" resolution are based on the fact that the 0.36" Band 6 fluxes (from the ALMA data we show in the proposal) are much higher than expected; i.e., the sources are extremely peaked.  See p. 3 of the science case for details.

Also, importantly, at 0.36" resolution the RMS will allow us to detect polarization not only in the cores, but also in the filamentary structure surrounding them.

Finally, based on prior CARMA and SMA data, all of the polarization detections in the Class 0 envelopes and disks will be well above the 0.1% systematic limit of the ALMA system.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator setup is the setup recommended for continuum polarization observations.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>SCIENCE GOAL 1: The requested 0.36" angular resolution matches that of our previous high-priority Cycle 2 proposal (2013.1.00726.S); this resolution was requested initially to probe the inner envelopes of the sources, which had been mapped in polarization with CARMA at ~2.5" resolution.

The largest angular scale matches the size of the largest structures seen in the Band 6 continuum maps shown in Figure 1.


SCIENCE GOAL 2: The 0.08" resolution requested in Science Case 2 will allow us to map the B-field orientation where the innermost part of the envelope meets the outer disk.  

The largest angular scale is set such that we only need to use one configuration (C36-6), and so that the UV coverage will overlap with the data from Science Goal 1 (which has a resolution of 0.36", smaller than the 1.4" MRS in Science Goal 2).
 

Regarding the primary beam restriction: extended emission is inevitable in any star-forming region. However, the cores we are observing have strongly peaked dust continuum emission, and those peaks will easily fit inside the inner third of the 345 GHz primary beam (see Figure 1).
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
